Eurozone inflation slumped to 0.1% in August
Consumer prices in the euro area rose only slightly in August, by 0.1% year-on-year, according to Eurostat, the EU statistical authority.
The rise in prices was driven down by lower energy prices.
Eurostat thus revised its 0.2% estimate a few weeks ago slightly downwards.
In July, inflation stood at 0.2%.
In August, the so-called underlying inflation fell to 0.9 per cent from 1.0 per cent in July.
Eurostat's estimate of underlying inflation was 1.0 per cent.
Energy in the euro area last month was 7.2 per cent cheaper than a year ago.
In the EU as a whole, the average inflation rate in the 28 countries was zero in August.
In July, the increase was 0.1 per cent.
Of the euro area, consumer prices rose most, i.e. by 1.4%, in Malta in August.
In Cyprus, inflation was lowest at 1.9%.
In Finland, inflation was 0.2 per cent down on the EU's harmonised price index.
Euro area inflation remains persistently far from the European Central Bank’s (ECB) target, which is an increase in prices close to 2% in the medium term.
The ECB forecasts an average inflation rate of 0.1% in the euro area for this year.
Next year, the increase will increase to 1.1%, the central bank predicts its release at the beginning of September in its new inflation forecasts.
US Fed to try to tighten monetary policy
The next US recession will start at its fastest in less than a year, but more certainly in three years after the Federal Reserve Federation starts to raise its interest rates again for a long time.
And in the financial markets, the downturn begins before the next recession.
The Fed has hinted that it might start raising interest rates this week and by the end of the year at the latest.
Thus, the next recession can be pushed on at its fastest by next autumn, and as a financial market price rumble before that.
Or at least that is what happens if the world's largest economy and financial markets function as they used to do - and if they react to the tightening of the Fed's money taps as they have done before.
Such conclusions have been drawn by Jim Reid, Nick Burns and Seb Barker of Deutsche Bank's London market research strategies in their extensive research on long-term market and economic cycles.
The Bank distributed a 60-page Long-Term Asset Return Study to its international major customers last week.
The strategies behind the study and report do not believe they know exactly when the Fed will start raising its interest rates or what will happen in the economy and the market after that.
Instead, they use their cool facts and calculations to show how the economy and the market have behaved in the past during and since the Fed interest rate hikes.
In addition to historical observations, they look at what key economic and financial market variables are now on the same or different pattern as at the time of previous interest rate hikes - and what might result from that.
It is clear that both the economy and the financial markets are now in a more shaky condition to bear the rise in interest rates than they were before in the 1950s.
A year may not be the beginning of a recession
The leaders of the Fed’s monetary policy and its respective stance have all hinted over the past summer and early autumn that the time is beginning to be ripe for interest rate increases.
The first interest rate increase in more than nine years can take place this week.
The matter will be resolved within Wednesday and Thursday, when the so-called Open Market Committee of the Fed Board meets to decide on the matter for its two-day meeting.
The last time the Fed raised its so-called Fed funds interest rate was in June 2006.
At that time, a series of relatively regular but small interest rate hikes of 0.25 percentage points over a period of two years ended, with the Fed raising its interest rate from 1.25% to 5.25%.
Financial market symptoms began in 2007 with the most risky housing financing problems in the United States, and a year later, the financial crisis broke into a global doomsday nightmare.
The Great Recession came in 2009.
The last time the financial markets and the real economy were hit harder than they have been since the previous Fed interest rate hikes.
Similarly, the trials were tougher and harsher than ever since the recession of the 1930s.
Deutsche's strategies have screened the world's largest economic ups and downs, as well as financial market trends since 1950 and in some places since the early nineteenth century.
The Fed’s interest rate hikes and their economic and financial impact will be reported from the 1950s onwards.
The fastest period since the start of the recession is less than a year, most often less than three years and on average less than three and a half years.
The increase in the financial markets has ended within one to two years of the start of the Fed’s interest rate hikes.
Since the early 1950s, the Fed has increased and decreased its key interest rate by a dozen cycles.
Each time has deviated from the others in some respects, and there are relatively few times in the review, so it is hardly possible to conclude with any certainty about the effects of the following interest rate hikes.
The strategies remind us that this time many things are different.
And not only better.
Interest rates too low for too long
The decisive causes of the financial crisis, let alone the culprits, may not be undisputed, even with decades of research.
But there are three factors that lead to the crisis and increase its destructive power, which are perhaps indisputably clear:
1) In the 2000s, the Fed, the euro area ECB and other major central banks kept their interest rates too low for too long.
They patched the traces of the technobubble, and at the same time raised the next one.
2) Over the decades, the accumulation of debt in different parts of the financial and real economy, and the already excessive amount of debt, increased even further under the influence of central banks’ excess monetary policy.
The biggest debt bubble in the history of the economy so far was born.
3) In particular, the almost undistributed crazy debt financing in the financial economy swelled the largest exchange rate bubbles in the history of the financial markets from shares to real estate, bonds and commodities.
There is hardly much controversy about this, either, that the financial markets, rising to heights due to increasingly complex leverages, were in a very dangerous and volatile situation when the Fed and other central banks last pushed interest rates upwards.
The financial structures tuned to leverage, let alone valuation bubbles, could only last a long time after interest rate increases had begun and the cost of debt financing had risen.
The risks were realised as a financial crisis, followed by a major recession.
Bigger bubble and more debt
Deutsche’s strategies do not guess what will happen next, but give rise to criticism, for example by mentioning the following:
1) The Fed and other major central banks have now kept their monetary policy stance even lighter even longer than before the financial crisis.
If the interest rates were too low before the crisis for too long, they have now been even lower for longer.
2) Indebtedness has for a long time not been crazy cheap as it was ten years ago, but now debt money is literally cheaper than free money.
Thus, the debt burden in the financial and real economy has not eased, but now the debt burden in different parts of the economy is much heavier than before the financial crisis or ever before.
3) Liquidity from central banks has largely remained in the financial markets, and has lashed the most important securities and assets to the most expensive ones, either before the financial crisis or ever.
And not only do the strategies latish the atmosphere with financial market warning signs, but they also point out that even the US economy has not yet recovered from the financial crisis and decades since the heaviest recession to the model it has seen in the past.
The euro area economy has barely recovered at all.
In other words, the real economy is in an unusually weak condition, but similarly, the pressures and risks on the financial markets are incomparably higher than before the financial crisis, when the Fed next begins to tighten its money taps tighter.
Perhaps the future image of Albert Edwards, the strategist of the French bank Societe Generale, is not as strange as it might seem.
For some time now, he has been preparing the Bank’s international investor clients for Fed’s following translations:
First the Fed raises interest rates, then the financial bubbles break out - and soon it will be time for the Fed to rush to extinguish the financial blocks with even larger QE cash syringes.
