This week, the U.S. central bank’s decision makers are sitting around a huge mahogany table for two days in a long-awaited meeting to decide whether it’s time to raise the key interest rate for the first time in almost a decade.
At the other end of the central bank’s decorative, two-storey meeting room is a mural from the United States.
The map is a reminder that the President of the Central Bank, Janet L. Yellen, and her colleagues must put the nation's financial interests above all else.
Congress has put two responsibilities on the shoulders of the Central Bank: to maximise employment in the United States and to keep prices stable.
However, since the Great Depression, the Bank’s executives have accepted that there is also a third unwritten mandate: financial stability.
It is this third requirement that can be decisive in a public decision on Thursday, which is so strict that it cannot even be predicted. The decision on whether the US economy is ready to be weaned from the record-breaking incentive brought by short-term interest rates that have remained close to zero since late 2008.
While most of the data shows that the economy is growing steadily, the recent turmoil in the global financial markets may have made the already cautious central bank officials increasingly timid as regards increasing volatility.
Understandably, the labour market and inflation are the first and most important factors to be monitored,” says Lindsey M. Piegza, chief financial expert at the brokerage firm Stifel Nicolaus & Co.
However, I believe that if they are looking for justification for a return on interest rates, the increased uncertainty in the world market is enough to wait,” he says.
There has been no agreement on the decision of the Central Bank, which also gives rise to nervousness in the economy.
According to a recent study by Bloomberg, about half of the economists predict that interest rates will rise this week.
The financial markets, on the other hand, expect the central bank to delay the withdrawal, as the key indicator indicates that the potential for growth is only around 30%.
This suggests a fall in the securities market if the central bank raises the level, if the decision-makers did not succeed in softening the shock by promising that the next draw will not take place in the near future.
On Tuesday, the Dow Jones industrial average index rose by 228.89 points, or 1.4 per cent, with a new figure of 16 599.85.
The recovery was brought about by the expectation that the central bank will maintain its level this week, says John Lonski, Chief Financial Officer of Moody’s Capital Markets Research Group.
It will be surprising if the central bank raises interest rates right now,” he says.
If the decision-makers raise interest rates, “they have to make a lot of effort in their policy to support the financial markets so that they do not panic.”
Other experts argue that an elevated level would calm down the financial markets as it would eliminate uncertainty about when the central bank will operate.
Just a month ago, it seemed that the central bank would be raising interest rates by a quarter of a percentage point this month, thus taking the first small step towards slow tightening the monetary situation, which would ensure the stability of the US recovery.
Yellen has stated in the spring and early summer that he expects the level to rise this year, despite the fact that liberals are demanding more economic development in their election.
Although job creation slowed down in August, labour market growth has been stable this year.
The unemployment rate fell last month to 5.1%, which is the lowest figure in seven years and close to the level that the central bank considers to be the limit for full employment.
Wage growth has shown signs of recovery.
Although inflation is still below the central bank’s 2% annual target, the main reason for this is the temporary impact of lowered oil prices.
The economy will “survive and also need larger interest rates, taking into account the tight labour market situation,” says Ian Shepherdson, Chief Financial Officer at Pantheon Macroeconomics.
However, financial markets around the world were shaken last week when China devalued its currency.
The Dow Jones Industrial Average index fell by up to 16 percent from its May record, when investors feared that China would slow down global growth.
The market has recovered somewhat this month, and the Dow index is now close to 10% below the peak in May.
For the central bank’s decision-makers, the turmoil in the market is an additional factor in a complex equation that explains why interest rates need to be raised.
Without these financial market events and recent weeks’ news about China’s economic weakness, policymakers would be tightening the level at this meeting,” said Stephen D. Oliner, a specialist researcher at UCLA Ziman Center for Real Estate and a former central bank official.
Now he predicts that decision-makers will wait at least a month to get a better understanding of the effects.
The possible impact on the US economy is still quite unclear and they do not have much information at their disposal as regards the consequences of the events in China,” said Oliner.
The well-being of the international economy is not the central bank’s main concern, so in principle it should not affect decision-making.
In practice, however, the Federal Reserve has become the world's monetary authority.
In recent years, the influence of the Central Bank has been enormous.
In 2013, then President Ben S. Bernanke's suggestion that the central bank could "decrease" the amount of money caused upheavals in the markets around the world.
In a world where markets and economies are increasingly intertwined, central bank officials are expected not only to monitor developments elsewhere, but also to consult other central banks and experts to gain a better understanding of the global economy.
The central bank’s decision-making process is “more art than science,” says Zachary Karabell, Head of Global Strategy at Envestnet Inc.
Jeffrey Lacker, President of the Federal Reserve Bank in Richmond, Virginia, said this month that “the central bank has previously overreacted to financial market movements that appeared to be distinct from the fundamentals of the economy.”
The Federal Open Market Committee, which is making decisions, has called for an increase in interest rates, and Lacker, a member of the Committee with the right to vote, calls for example for 1998-99 decisions.
The Asian economic crisis caused the central bank to cut its benchmark by 0.75 percentage points during three meetings, “despite its limited, recognisable impact on US economic growth,” says Lacker.
A year later, these cuts were cancelled by the central bank.
The central bank should put economic stability first only during a major crisis, as the market collapsed in 2008, says Adam S. Posen, a former member of the Bank of England’s interest rate committee.
The latest turbulence is nowhere near its level, Posen says.
No one wants to be in a situation where raising interest rates is feared because the market is getting upset,” says Posen, Chairman of the Peterson Institute for International Economics.
The Federal Reserve Act still contains a twofold requirement and does not mention financial stability. As long as this is the case, I do not think they should anticipate it.
