Weight loss surgery can help mildly obese diabetics
According to a new study, the benefits of weight loss surgery for mildly obese type 2 diabetics can last at least five years.
However, it is still too early to say whether these mildly obese diabetics live longer after surgery than those treated in other ways than surgery.
It takes a long time to get the mortality data,” says Dr. Robin Blackstone, a weight loss surgery specialist who wrote the editorial for a new study in the journal JAMA Surgery.
For weight loss or bariatric surgery, different methods are used to reduce the size of the stomach.
They reduce the feeling of hunger and limit the absorption of food.
Over the years, bariatric surgeries have been found to be effective for the treatment of type 2 diabetes, but the majority of subjects in the study have been hospitalized obese, and their BMI has been 35 or more.
BMI, or weight-to-length ratio, is considered normal when it is between 18.5 and 24.9.
If the BMI is more than 25, it indicates that someone is overweight, and if the BMI is more than 30, they are considered to be obese.
You can calculate your BMI here: 1.usa.gov/1D0ZqDv.
For this new study, researchers at the Taiwan-based Min-Sheng General Hospital used data collected since 2007 to compare two types of bariatric surgery, gastric bypass surgery, and gastric miniaturization, to the treatment of type 2 diabetes in people who were mildly obese.
The study showed that the average BMI fell from 31 to 24.5 by the end of the fifth year.
At the same time, the BMI of those treated by means other than surgery remained roughly the same at 29.
Thirty-six per cent of the people who had had surgery had a complete and 28 per cent partial improvement in diabetes.
For comparison, in the medically treated group, diabetes improved completely by only 1% and partially by about 2%.
In addition, blood pressure, triglycerides and “bad” LDL cholesterol “were generally better in the surgery group,” the authors said.
The researchers also monitored the blood hemoglobin A1c levels in patients, reflecting the long-term blood sugar levels.
Haemoglobin A1c should remain below 7%, the researchers write.
Postoperative hemoglobin A1c levels dropped from about 9% to about 6%.
However, in the medical treatment group, it remained stable at about 8%.
However, this improved “glycemic control” described by improved hemoglobin A1c levels did not reduce mortality over a five-year period, says Chief Research Scientist Chih-Cheng Hsu and colleagues.
The study group also compared average results between two different types of surgery.
For the fifth year, when compared to a group that had undergone gastric surgery, the group that had undergone gastric bypass surgery had lost more weight (18.7 and 14.2 kg), decreased their body mass index more (7.4 and 5.1), decreased their hemoglobin A1c levels more (3.1 and 2.1%), and was more likely to achieve complete diabetes remission (46.9% and 16.7%).
The University of Arizona College of Medicine-Phoenix Blackstone says that while the study does not show survival or surgery after five years, there are research results from Sweden where surgery led to a longer life in heavier people.
A Swedish study found that obese people undergoing weight loss surgery had a 29 percent lower probability of dying over a 15-year period when compared to a group that had tried more traditional treatments.
Although the new study does not show any improvement in the survival of surgical patients, Blackstone says that the results are encouraging for those with less than 35 BMI who are interested in surgery.
The results of the study are crucial precisely because they show that surgery is safe for the lower body mass index group,” he says, without the increased risk of death or kidney disease.
Blackstone adds that both patients and their physicians should take weight very seriously when the patient's BMI is between 27 and 30.
I think we wait too long before we take this seriously,” he says.
I believe that when a person has accumulated these genetic changes that permanently prepare his body for obesity and diabetes, it will be very difficult to reverse the situation.
