Xi calls for the opening of the economy to the wider world
The economy must open up more to the outside world in order to promote growth, President Xi Jinping told the group on Tuesday, whose task is to steer reform.
China should commit itself to attracting foreign finance and expertise and developing a policy of openness," he said at the 16th meeting of the lead group on deepening the overall reform.
Supporting transparency while driving forward reforms will bring new momentum and vitality, and will create new space for economic growth, Xi said.
The Management Group adopted a series of guidelines, including a negative list of market access restrictions, a loosening of border control principles, an invitation to state-owned companies to seize private capital, and a review of the resident registration system.
According to the opinion, a negative list will be created that will identify the sectors and companies to which no investment is allowed.
The system will be gradually tested and improved through pilot programmes.
The change is significant, as it gives the market a greater role in allocating resources, ensuring a legal business environment and making the market more transparent, the opinion states.
The government also loosens its control over the power it distributes to companies, thus ensuring that companies decide for themselves how to run their business.
The opinion also said that China would allow border regions to explore new models of cross-border economic cooperation as well as new mechanisms for developing regional growth.
In order to open up government-controlled sectors to private financiers, more sectors are opening up.
The government will not change its policy on foreign investment and will protect the legitimate interests of foreign-funded companies and provide them with better services,” the statement said.
In addition, the application process for foreign permanent resident permits, “green cards”, is facilitated by optimising the requirements and lightening the application process.
The meeting also discussed the safeguarding of the rights of lawyers to practise and the support of professional judges and prosecutors.
The meeting was also attended by Prime Minister Li Keqiang, as well as senior leaders Liu Yunshan and Zhang Gaoli, in a statement published after the meeting.
